{"title_page": "Tornadoes of 2020", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Notable tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in 2020}}\n{{Infobox tornado year\n|name          = Tornadoes of 2020\n|image         = 2020 United States tornado count.png\n|caption       = A chart of the 2020 United States tornado count estimated from the number of preliminary reports\n|timespan      = January 3 \u2013 ongoing\n|max_EF        = EF4\n|max_location  = 5 different locations\n|max_date      = 4 different days\n|tornadoes_usa = 445\n|total_damages_usa = >$4.4&nbsp;billion\n|total_fatalities_world = 74\n|total_fatalities_usa = 74\n|year = 2020\n}}\n\nThis page documents notable [[tornado]]es and [[tornado outbreak]]s worldwide in '''2020'''. Strong and destructive tornadoes form most frequently in the [[United States]], [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], [[Bangladesh]], and [[East India|Eastern India]], but can occur almost anywhere under the right conditions. Tornadoes also develop occasionally in southern [[Canada]] during the [[Northern Hemisphere]]'s summer and somewhat regularly at other times of the year across [[Europe]], [[Asia]], [[Argentina]], [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]]. Tornadic events are often accompanied by other forms of [[severe weather]], including strong [[thunderstorm]]s, strong [[winds]], and [[hail]].\n\nThere have been 581 preliminary filtered reports of tornadoes in the United States in 2020,<ref>{{cite web |title=Annual Severe Weather Report Summary 2020 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/online/monthly/2020_annual_summary.html |publisher=Storm Prediction Center |accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref> of which at least 445 have been confirmed. Worldwide, 74 tornado-related deaths have been confirmed, all in the United States.\n\n==Events==\n{{Tornadoes of 2020/Deadly}}\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020|List of United States tornadoes in April 2020}}\n\n===United States yearly total===\n<!-- This section is transcluded to other articles; modify with caution. -->\n<onlyinclude>\n{{Tornado Chart\n|Total = 445\n|FU = 10\n|F0 = 132\n|F1 = 218\n|F2 = 65\n|F3 = 15\n|F4 = 5\n|F5 = 0\n| Enhanced=yes\n}}\n</onlyinclude>\n\n==January==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#January}}\nThere were 90 tornadoes reported in the United States in January, of which 88 were confirmed. Overall, January was an active month, with over twice the national average of 35 tornadoes.\n\n===January 3 (South Africa)===\nOn January 3, severe thunderstorms developed over the [[Mpumalanga]] province of [[South Africa]]. One thunderstorm developed into a supercell which produced an EF3 tornado that caused significant damage to a farm, destroyed the houses of seven families, and destroyed about {{convert|200|hectare|acre|sigfig=1}} of pine forest.<ref>{{cite web |title=Media Release: Panbult tornado (Mpumalanga) on the 3rd of January 2020. |url=https://twitter.com/SAWeatherServic/status/1214087467692941312?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1214087467692941312&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.news24.com%2FSouthAfrica%2FNews%2Fwatch-tornado-lasting-about-40-minutes-destroyed-farm-and-7-houses-in-mpumalanga-saws-confirms-20200106 |website=Twitter |publisher=South African Weather Service |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===January 10\u201311===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of January 10\u201311, 2020}}\n{{stack begin}}{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 25|EF1= 41|EF2= 13|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=0}}{{stack end}}\n[[File:Carollton EF2 damage1.jpg|thumb|left|High-end EF2 damage to a house near Carrollton, Alabama.]]\nOn January 10, the Storm Prediction Center issues a moderate risk of severe weather for much of the Southern United States, including a 15% hatched risk of tornadoes. A squall line of severe thunderstorms with numerous embedded circulations and semi-discrete supercell structures moved from [[Texas]] and [[Oklahoma]] to the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]], producing numerous tornadoes. A high-end EF2 tornado near [[Carrollton, Alabama]] destroyed multiple homes and mobile homes, and resulted in three fatalities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Three people killed in Pickens Co. tornado |url=https://www.wbrc.com/2020/01/11/three-people-killed-pickens-co-tornado/ |publisher=WBRC |accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Three people were fatally injured when a long-tracked EF2 tornado destroyed two mobile homes south of [[Haughton, Louisiana]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Enfinger |first1=Emily |title=87-year-old dies from injuries from Haughton tornado |url=https://eu.shreveporttimes.com/story/news/local/2020/01/15/third-death-confimred-haughton-tornado/4480014002/ |publisher=Shreveport Times |accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref> and an EF1 tornado killed one person near [[Nacogdoches, Texas]] when a large tree fell onto a mobile home.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brackett |first1=Ron |last2=Wesner Childs |first2=Jan |title=Tornadoes, Severe Storms Kill 8; More Than 300,000 Lose Power |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-01-11-severe-storms-tornadoes-impact-texas-louisiana-tennessee-arkansas-mississippi |website=weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=January 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Houston, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey for January 10 Burleson County Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSHGX&e=202001112109|date=January 11, 2020|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> An EF2 tornado struck [[Rome, Mississippi]], causing significant damage and destroying the local post office. An EF2 tornado also struck [[Union Grove, Alabama]], significantly damaging a school building in the community. Another school also sustained major damage near [[Kershaw, South Carolina]], as a result of another EF2 tornado. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 79 tornadoes, and resulted in 7 fatalities. Total damage from the event reached $1.1&nbsp;billion according to the [[National Centers for Environmental Information]].<ref name=\"NCEI_billion\">{{cite web|publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information|year=2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Billion-Dollar Weather and Climate Disasters: Events|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/billions/events}}</ref>\n\n==February==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#February}}\nThere were 51 tornadoes reported in the United States in February, of which 42 were confirmed. February was also an active month, besting the national average of 29 tornadoes.\n\n===February 5\u20137===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 21|EF2= 6|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=1}}\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of February 5\u20137, 2020}}\n[[File:KannapolisNCEF2-2020.jpg|thumb|left|EF2 damage to a house near Kannapolis, North Carolina.]]\nBeginning on February 5, a moderate tornado outbreak affected the Deep South and Eastern United States. On the first day of the outbreak, an EF2 tornado caused significant tree and outbuilding damage near [[Pickens, Mississippi]], and injured four people. A long-tracked EF2 tornado touched down near [[Bay Springs, Mississippi]] and passed though the town of [[Enterprise, Clarke County, Mississippi|Enterprise]], downing numerous trees and power poles and toppling a metal fire tower. This tornado tore large sections of roofing off of multiple homes in rural areas as well. On February 6, one person was killed in [[Marengo County, Alabama]] when an EF1 tornado destroyed a mobile home near [[Demopolis, Alabama|Demopolis]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/06/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202002070055|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Jackson, Mississippi|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/05/2020 \u2013 02/06/2020 Tornado Event \u2013 Update #1|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSJAN&e=202002070252|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref> An EF2 tornado also touched down near [[Kannapolis, North Carolina]], to the north of [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]]. No injuries were reported, though multiple homes were damaged, including one that lost its roof and some exterior walls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/06/tornado-touches-down-kannapolis/|title=Tornado touches down in Kannapolis|website=WBTV|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/confirmed-tornado-damages-homes-in-kannapolis/275-3a51f749-53cd-490f-bf2c-3fd08c8c793c|title=Confirmed tornado damages homes in the Kannapolis area|website=WCNC|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Tornado rips roof off home in Kannapolis, North Carolina|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gE8N-dBHI7k|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> Another EF2 downed metal truss transmission towers near [[Kings Mountain, North Carolina|Kings Mountain]], and an EF1 tornado caused damage in the southern suburbs of Charlotte.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://salisburypost.com/2020/02/08/three-rescued-from-flood-waters-weather-service-confirms-tornado-in-rowan-county/|title=As flooding, damage lingers, 3 rescued from Third Creek, weather service confirms tornadoes in Rowan|last=Walker|first=Shavonne|work=[[Salisbury Post]]|date=2020-02-08|accessdate=2020-02-08}}</ref><ref name=WBTV>{{cite news|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/07/nws-confirms-ef-tornado-near-pineville/|title=NWS confirms EF-1 tornado near Pineville|last=Myers|first=Jason|work=[[WBTV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/tornado-stanly-albemarle-damage-storm/275-227d0b28-9341-4b91-a7a0-057602e4a803|title=EF-1 tornado confirmed near Albemarle|work=[[WCNC-TV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> A high-end EF1 tornado moved directly through [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]] as well, causing considerable damage to homes and businesses.<ref name=WBTV/> On February 7, five tornadoes touched down in Maryland, including an EF1 that struck [[Westminster, Maryland|Westminster]] and [[Manchester, Maryland|Manchester]], causing moderate damage. An EF0 tornado also caused minor damage in [[Leesburg, Virginia]]. Along with the tornadic storms, heavy rainfall resulted in widespread flooding also occurred throughout the southern states. Total economic losses from the event exceeded $925&nbsp;million. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 37 tornadoes, and resulted in one fatality.<ref>{{cite report|publisher=Aon|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Global Catastrophe Recap: February 2020|url=http://thoughtleadership.aonbenfield.com/Documents/20200309_analytics-if-february-global-recap.pdf|page=4|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n==March==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#March}}\nThere were 106 tornadoes reported in the United States in March, of which 78 were confirmed. Although March was just about average in number of tornadoes, the series of severe weather outbreaks and tornadoes throughout March inflicted widespread damage across the country. Combined economic losses reached approximately $2.4&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|author=Matt Sheehan|publisher=Reinsurance News|date=April 14, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Separate billion-dollar events mark active month for US tornadoes: Aon|url=https://www.reinsurancene.ws/separate-billion-dollar-events-mark-active-month-for-us-tornadoes-aon/}}</ref>\n\n===March 2\u20133===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of March 2\u20133, 2020}}\n[[File:CookevilleTNEF4rubbleanddamage.jpg|thumb|left|EF4 damage in a residential area near Cookeville, Tennessee.]]\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 3|EF2= 4|EF3= 1|EF4= 1|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nA small but devastating tornado outbreak affected parts of the Southern United States on the evening of March 2 into the early morning hours of March 3, with the most severe damage and all fatalities occurring in Tennessee. [[Nashville, Tennessee]] was directly struck by a high-end EF3 tornado just after 12:30&nbsp;a.m. CDT on March 3. Major structural damage and six fatalities occurred as the tornado passed just north of downtown Nashville and through [[Mount Juliet, Tennessee|Mount Juliet]] to the east. Additional tornadoes were reported in [[Missouri]], [[Alabama]], [[Tennessee]], and [[Kentucky]]. An EF2 tornado killed one person and caused significant damage to homes, mobile homes, and outbuildings near [[Camden, Tennessee]] as well. The majority of the deaths occurred in Putnam County, where a violent EF4 tornado touched down near [[Baxter, Tennessee|Baxter]] shortly before 2:00&nbsp;a.m. and moved into western [[Cookeville, Tennessee|Cookeville]]. Many homes and other buildings were completely leveled or swept away in residential areas of Cookeville, and 19 people were killed in town.<ref name=\"OHX\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=March 2\u20133, 2020 Tornadoes and Severe Weather|url=https://www.weather.gov/ohx/20200303|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=March 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=21 killed, 221 hospitalized after tornadoes rip through Nashville, surrounding areas|url=https://www.abcactionnews.com/news/national/six-killed-at-least-20-hurt-after-tornadoes-rip-through-nashville-surrounding-areas|publisher=ABC Action News|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> In addition, two EF2 tornadoes also downed numerous trees in forested areas near [[Alvaton, Kentucky]] and [[Clarkrange, Tennessee]] as well. A lone, long-tracked [[supercell]] thunderstorm was responsible for all nine of the tornadoes in Tennessee as it moved from near [[Dyersburg, Tennessee|Dyersburg]] in West Tennessee to near [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] in East Tennessee. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 14 tornadoes, and resulted in 26 fatalities.<ref name=\"OHX\"/>\n\n===March 18\u201319===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 11|EF2= 5|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nOn March 18, an intense [[supercell thunderstorm]] spawned numerous weak tornadoes as it tracked through [[Jack County, Texas|Jack]], [[Stephens County, Texas|Stephens]], [[Wise County, Texas|Wise]], and [[Young County, Texas|Young counties]] in [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Fort Worth, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/18/2020 Tornado Event \u2013 Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSFWD&e=202003201858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> With severe storms continuing into the early morning hours of March 19, two EF2 tornadoes caused considerable damage to trees, vehicles, farming equipment, and outbuildings near [[Trent, Texas]].<ref name=\"SJT0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in San Angelo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event \u2013 Update #1|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSSJT&e=202003201627|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The thunderstorm responsible for those tornadoes went on to produce another EF2 tornado that damaged a large building and over 100 cars at a correctional facility northeast of [[Abilene, Texas|Abilene]]. Near [[Sweetwater, Texas|Sweetwater]], an EF2 tornado damaged or destroyed several wind turbines.<ref name=\"SJT0319\"/> Later that day, a large portion of the southern [[Great Plains]] was in line for severe storms, along with parts of the [[Ohio Valley]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Darrow|title=Mar 19, 2020 0100 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2020/day1otlk_20200319_0100.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> During the afternoon, a squall line with several embedded supercells formed from [[Oklahoma]] to [[Indiana]], producing tornadoes in [[Oklahoma]], [[Illinois]], and [[Arkansas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tulsa, Oklahoma|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTSA&e=202003210250|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PAH0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003202132|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"LZK0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornadoes Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003212158|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 21, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> A large EF2 tornado touched down near [[Everton, Arkansas]] before moving through the southeastern part of town, causing significant damage to homes, a school, outbuildings, and trees.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> Three EF1 tornadoes also touched down in Arkansas, one of which tracked between [[Gassville, Arkansas|Gassville]] and [[Mountain Home, Arkansas|Mountain Home]], inflicting considerable damage to some homes. Further north, two EF1 tornadoes caused damage in [[Sunfield, Illinois|Sunfield]] and [[Dahlgren, Illinois]].<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> One person was injured in Illinois,<ref name=\"PAH0319\"/> and another injury occurred in Arkansas. A total of 21 tornadoes were confirmed.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/>\n\n===March 28\u201329===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 3|EF1= 11|EF2= 2|EF3= 1|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 3}}\nOn March 28, the SPC issued a moderate risk of severe weather for much of Illinois, including a 15% hatched risk of tornadoes. An enhanced risk of severe weather was in place \nacross parts of Iowa, Missouri, Indiana, and Arkansas as well. Only weak tornadoes touched down in the moderate risk area, though a few strong tornadoes occurred elsewhere. A large EF3 tornado struck the city of [[Jonesboro, Arkansas]], while being streamed live on local news stations, producing major damage to homes, businesses, and a shopping mall. Vehicles were thrown and mangled, and the local airport sustained severe damage as well. A train was also derailed, and 22 injuries occurred in Jonesboro.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado flattens buildings in Jonesboro, Arkansas, as severe weather moves across the Midwest, Lower Mississippi River Valley |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/28/weather/tornadoes-severe-storms-forecast-saturday/index.html |website=CNN |publisher=CNN |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Damage Reported in Northeastern Arkansas as Tornado Strikes Jonesboro |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-03-28-severe-weather-tornado-impacts-plains-south-midwest |website=Weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"20200328 reports\">{{cite web |title=Today's Storm Reports (20200328 1200 UTC \u2013 20200329 1159 UTC) (Print Version) |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200328_rpts.html|website=NOAA |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Memphis, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMEG&e=202003292239|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Zoellner |first1=Danielle |title=Tornado rips through Arkansas town, injuring six people |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/arkansas-tornado-jonesboro-weather-injured-a9432511.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\nThe same storm that produced this tornado also produced two EF1 tornadoes, one before and one after it moved over Jonesboro.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003292104|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\"/>\nInto the evening, numerous weak tornadoes touched down in [[Iowa]] and [[Illinois]], and another in southwest [[Wisconsin]]. This included an EF1 tornado that caused moderate damage to apartment buildings and trees in [[Oelwein, Iowa]].<ref name=\"20200328 reports\"/>\nA low-end EF2 tornado moved through the southern fringes of [[Henderson, Kentucky]], destroying numerous outbuildings and a barn, and damaging dozens of homes and trees.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Henderson County KY Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300139|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\nAnother EF2 struck the town of [[Newburgh, Indiana]], where five homes sustained partial to total roof removal, and one home had a few upper floor exterior walls ripped off. Numerous other homes in town sustained less severe damage, and two people were injured in Newburgh.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Newburgh Indiana Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300138|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarly in the morning of March 29, the same storm system produced an EF0 tornado that mainly damaged trees near [[Sparta, Tennessee]]. Overall, this outbreak produced 20 tornadoes.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/29/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSOHX&e=202003311858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March 30\u201331===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 3|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 2}}\nOn the evening of March 30, isolated supercells developed across Texas and Oklahoma, producing two weak tornadoes. One of these was given an EFU rating, and the other, which was a [[landspout]] or non-mesocylonic tornado, was given an EF0 rating.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Amarillo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/30/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSAMA&e=202003312336|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> \nOn March 31, multiple supercells and embedded mesocyclones formed along and just ahead of a convective line, producing several tornadoes across parts of the [[Southeastern United States]].<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\">{{cite web |title=SPC Storm reports for03/31/20 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200331_rpts.html |publisher=Storm Prediction |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\nA high-end EF2 tornado caused significant damage just south of [[Eufaula, Alabama]], where multiple homes in a subdivision had their roofs torn off. A few of these homes sustained partial exterior wall loss.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fuentes |first1=Carmen |title=Eufaula tornado runs through neighborhood |url=https://www.wtvy.com/content/news/Eufaula-tornado-runs-through-neighborhood-569268011.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |agency=WTVY |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202004020401|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> Multiple other weak tornadoes were confirmed in southeast [[Mississippi]], southern [[Alabama]], and northern [[Florida]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee, Florida|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=202004032145|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 3, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\"/> A landspout tornado was caught on video around 2:30&nbsp;p.m. PDT at the north edge of [[Richland, Washington]], causing no damage. A total of 15 tornadoes are confirmed.<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\"/>\n\n==April==\n{{see also|List of United States tornadoes in April 2020}}\nThere have been 339 tornadoes reported in the United States this April, of which 238 have been confirmed.\n\n===April 7\u20139===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 20|EF1= 10|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nA few weak tornadoes touched down across [[Ohio]] and [[Pennsylvania]] late on April 7 and into the early morning of April 8, causing tree and structure damage. Later on the night of April 8, a large EF2 cone tornado touched down near [[Weiner, Arkansas]], completely destroying a mobile home. The tornado then struck [[Harrisburg, Arkansas]] in [[Poinsett County, Arkansas|Poinsett County]].<ref>https://twitter.com/nwsmemphis/status/1248334194377232384?s=21</ref><ref>https://media.arkansasonline.com/img/photos/2020/04/09/storm1_t800.jpg?90232451fbcadccc64a17de7521d859a8f88077d</ref> In Harrisburg, one frail home was completely leveled by the tornado, and several homes nearby were also badly damaged or destroyed in residential areas of town.<ref>https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2020/apr/09/forecasters-tornado-touched-down-overnight-northwe/#.Xo9c00N8lmQ.twitter</ref> Extensive tree damage occurred and two people were injured in Harrisburg.<ref>https://twitter.com/kwoodallTV/status/1248076374084124673?s=19</ref> Numerous tornadoes, all of which weak and short-lived, occurred across [[Indiana]], [[Kentucky]], and Ohio that night as well. One EF1 tornado caused considerable damage to a brick building in downtown [[Mooresville, Indiana]]. Another EF1 tornado damaged two mobile homes, a garage, and trees near [[Wilkesville, Ohio]] on April 9 before the outbreak came to an end. Numerous reports of damaging straight line winds were also received throughout the event. A total of 31 tornadoes were confirmed.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\n=== April 12\u201313 ===\n{{Tornado chart small|FU = 0|F0 = 29|F1 = 75|F2 = 20|F3 = 12|F4 = 3|F5 = 0|Enhanced=yes}}\n{{main|2020 Easter tornado outbreak}}\n[[File:Cantwell Mill, Mississippi, April 12, 2020, tornado damage.jpg|thumb|left|High-end EF4 damage to a large, well-anchored cabin northeast of Bassfield, Mississippi.]]\nOn the morning of April 12, the SPC issued a moderate risk of severe weather for much of the [[Southern United States]], including a 15% risk of tornadoes. From the late morning of April 12 through the early morning of April 13, a major and deadly tornado outbreak unfolded across the region, with many strong to violent tornadoes touching down and causing major damage and numerous fatalities. Over a 48 hour period from nighttime on April 11 to the evening of April 13, 139 tornadoes touched down from Texas to Maryland. This event was well forecasted, with the [[Storm Prediction Center]] issuing severe weather outlooks as early as five days before the outbreak. At 10:40 a.m. CDT on April 12, a [[Particularly Dangerous Situation]] [[Tornado Watch]] was issued by the Storm Prediction Center across northeast [[Louisiana]], southeast [[Arkansas]], and central and northern [[Mississippi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0106.html|title=PDS Watch 106|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 11:44 a.m. CDT, a [[Tornado emergency|tornado emergency]] was issued for [[Monroe, Louisiana]] as an [[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF3 tornado]] moved through the city, causing significant damage to more than 200 homes, as well as the [[Monroe Regional Airport (Louisiana)|Monroe Regional Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.magnoliareporter.com/news_and_business/regional_news/article_4f3bcd2e-7ce3-11ea-8412-1b0152c3f85d.html|title=Magnolia Reporter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado Emergency for Monroe Louisiana and Northeast Ouachita Parish |url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=SVSSHV&e=202004121644 |website=Iowa Environmental Mesonet |publisher=National Weather Service Forecast Office in Shreveport, Louisiana |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SteveWAFB/status/1249799061898760192?s=20|title=Steve Caparotta of WAFB on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 3:30 p.m. CDT, two back-to-back supercells produced three intense and long-tracked tornadoes in southern Mississippi, including two rated EF4. The violent tornadoes promted the [[National Weather Service]] in [[Jackson, Mississippi]] to issue multiple tornado emergencies for numerous towns. The first of these two EF4 tornadoes leveled and swept away homes near [[Sartinville, Mississippi]], killing four. The second one reached high-end EF4 strength as it completely debarked trees, lofted vehicles hundreds of yards through the air, and obliterated well-built homes and structures in and around the towns of [[Bassfield, Mississippi|Bassfield]], [[Soso, Mississippi|Soso]], and [[Moss, Mississippi|Moss]]. This high-end EF4 tornado killed eight people, and was the largest tornado ever recorded in Mississippi state history. At 4:40 p.m. CDT, a second [[Particularly Dangerous Situation|PDS watch]] was issued affecting extreme southeast Mississippi and most of [[Alabama]], including the cities of [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]], [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]], [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]], and [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0110.html|title=Storm Prediction Center \u2013 PDS Watch 110|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As the system progressed northeastward into the nighttime hours, another tornado emergency was issued, this time at 11:28 p.m. EDT for the towns of [[Ooltewah, Tennessee|Ooltewah]] and [[Collegedale, Tennessee|Collegedale]] as a deadly EF3 tornado struck the eastern suburbs of [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]], killing three and injuring 19.<ref>https://twitter.com/NWSMorristown/status/1249735208460419073?s=20</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMRX&e=202004151915|title=NWS Morristown Damage Survey|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> A deadly EF2 tornado also impacted the small community of [[Sumac, Georgia]], destroying several mobile homes and killing seven people.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\nDuring the early morning hours April 13, the storms that formed the day before congealed into a strong [[squall line]] as they advanced into eastern [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] and the [[Carolinas]]. Multiple embedded circulations and semi-discrete supercells within the line spawned numerous strong and deadly tornadoes across the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSCharlestonSC/status/1249652455073370113?s=20|title=NWS Charleston SC on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/StuOstro/status/1250057470669721602</ref> Ten tornadoes of EF3 or greater strength occurred on day two of the outbreak, including eight in [[South Carolina]], where nine tornado-related fatalities occurred. The most significant tornado that occurred on April 13 was a 3/4-mile wide EF4 in [[Hampton County, South Carolina]] that destroyed many homes and took the lives of five people near [[Estill, South Carolina|Estill]] and [[Nixville, South Carolina|Nixville]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSCHS&e=202004152035|title=NWS Charleston Damage Survey|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Another high-end EF3 struck [[Seneca, South Carolina]], destroying multiple homes and a manufacturing plant, killing one person.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\nWith <!-- do not change this unless the fatality count has updated -->32<!-- as of April 20, only 32 fatalities have been confirmed to be tornado-related --> tornado-related fatalities, it was the deadliest outbreak since <!-- again, do not change to 2012 unless the TORNADO-RELATED fatality count exceeds 35 -->[[Tornado outbreak of April 27\u201330, 2014|April 27\u201330, 2014]].<ref>{{cite web |title=At Least 41 People Have Died After a Tornado Outbreak Ravaged the South |url=https://time.com/5820741/deadly-tornadoes-storms-south/ |website=TIME USA |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April 19\u201320===\n{{Tornado chart small|FU = 0|F0 = 5|F1 = 11|F2 = 3|F3 = 0|F4 = 1|F5 = 0|Enhanced=yes}}\nFor the second straight Sunday and Monday, several strong to violent tornadoes touched down across the Southern United States. On April 19, the SPC issued a moderate risk of severe weather for much of the Deep South, including a 15% hatched risk of tornadoes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Today's Storm Reports (20200419 1200 UTC \u2013 20200420 1159 UTC)|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200419_rpts.html|website=NOAA |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Later that evening, a large, violent EF4 tornado moved through  or near the rural Mississippi communities of [[Hurricane Creek, Mississippi|Hurricane Creek]], [[Sandy Hook, Mississippi|Sandy Hook]], [[Pine Burr, Mississippi|Pine Burr]], and areas north of [[Purvis, Mississippi]], killing one person and injuring another. A well-built house was leveled by this tornado, and numerous other homes and mobile homes were damaged or destroyed as well. Numerous trees were also snapped and partially debarked along the path.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in New Orleans|title=NWS New Orleans Tornado Report|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=LSRLIX&e=202004201907|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSJacksonMS/status/1252400542443122691|title=The Hurricane Creek/Pine Burr/Purvis/Camp Shelby tornado has been rated an EF-4 with estimated maximum wind of 170 MPH, path length of 54.2 miles, and maximum path width of 1.25 miles. Additional details will follow later this evening.|last=Jackson MS|first=NWS|date=2020-04-20|website=@NWSJacksonMS|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Later that evening, an EF2 tornado caused severe damage to a duplex, a home, some chicken houses, and other structures near [[Andalusia, Alabama]], injuring one person.<ref>{{cite web|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Mobile, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey for April 19, 2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMOB&e=202004212319|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> An EF1 tornado caused damage to multiple mobile homes and destroyed an RV camper near [[Robertsdale, Alabama]] as well, causing another injury.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMOB&e=202004210100|title=IEM :: PNS from NWS MOB|last=akrherz@iastate.edu|first=daryl herzmann|website=mesonet.agron.iastate.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> An EF2 tornado also struck the small community of [[Tumbleton, Alabama]], tearing the roofs off of some homes and a business, and causing one fatality when a mobile home was destroyed.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\nEarly on April 20, another EF2 tornado heavily damaged several homes and a mobile home near [[Bridgeboro, Georgia]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee FL|title=NWS Tallahassee FL Damage Survey|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=202004211628|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> Later on, several more tornadoes were reported throughout the morning into the afternoon in Central Florida.<ref>{{cite web|title=Today's Storm Reports (20200420 1200 UTC \u2013 20200421 1159 UTC)|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200420_rpts.html|website=NOAA |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> An EF0 tornado caused considerable damage to mobile homes and businesses in [[Homosassa, Florida|Homosassa]] and [[Homosassa Springs, Florida]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tampa Bay Ruskin FL|title=NWS Tampa Bay Ruskin FL Damage Survey|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTBW&e=202004201854|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chronicleonline.com/news/local/nws-tornado-causes-damage-in-homosassa-power-out-for-more-than-1-000-customers/article_ca25601c-831a-11ea-9981-a3a03237cc85.html|title=NWS: Tornado causes damage in Homosassa; power out for more than 1,000 customers|last=Thompson|first=Jeff Bryan & Buster|website=Chronicle Online|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Another EF0 tornado was caught on video lifting a stationary construction trailer across [[Interstate 75 in Florida|Interstate 75]] in [[Wildwood, Florida]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/PaulFox13/status/1252257783912824832|title=That'll stop traffic. Line of strong to severe thunderstorms across central #Florida produced this potential #tornado in Citrus county on I-75. #Skytower|last=DellegattoHigh voltage signFOX|first=Paul|date=2020-04-20|website=@PaulFox13|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsbreak.com/news/0OoG9ZmK/suspected-tornado-crosses-interstate-as-severe-weather-hits-central-florida|title=Suspected Tornado Crosses Interstate as Severe Weather Hits Central Florida|website=News Break|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> A total of 20 tornadoes were confirmed as a result of this outbreak, which resulted in two fatalities.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\n===April 22\u201323===\n{{Tornado chart small|FU = 0|F0 = 10|F1 = 21|F2 = 9|F3 = 1|F4 = 0|F5 = 0|Enhanced=yes}}\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of April 22\u201323, 2020}} \n[[File:MadillOklahoma-2020EF2damage.jpg|thumb|left|EF2 damage to a manufacturing facility in Madill, Oklahoma.]]\nOn the morning of April 22, the SPC issued an enhanced risk of severe weather for parts of Oklahoma, Texas, Louisiana, and Arkansas, which included a 10% hatched risk of tornadoes. Later that evening, multiple supercell thunderstorms developed and several tornadoes struck southern [[Oklahoma]] east of [[Interstate 35|I-35]], including a high-end EF2 tornado that killed two people and injured at least 30 others in [[Madill, Oklahoma|Madill]]. Industrial buildings were severely damaged at two manufacturing facilities in Madill, while a few homes and mobile homes in town were damaged or destroyed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Two people killed after tornado hits Marshall County, officials say |url=https://www.koco.com/article/person-killed-after-tornado-hits-marshall-county-officials-say/32243168 |accessdate=23 April 2020 |agency=KOCO News 5 |date=22 April 2020}}</ref> Several EF1 tornadoes also caused damage to homes, outbuildings, and trees near [[Wapanucka, Oklahoma|Wapanucka]], [[Pauls Valley, Oklahoma|Pauls Valley]], and [[Armstrong, Oklahoma|Armstrong]]. A deadly EF3 wedge tornado moved through [[San Jacinto County, Texas|San Jacinto]] and [[Polk County, Texas]] around 6:00 p.m. CDT, leaving three dead and causing severe damage in [[Onalaska, Texas|Onalaska]] and [[Seven Oaks, Texas|Seven Oaks]]. Numerous homes and mobile homes were damaged or destroyed along the path of this tornado, and 33 others were injured.<ref>https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200422_rpts.html</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSHouston/status/1253463558257471488?s=20|title=NWS Houston on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The same cell warranted [[tornado emergency|tornado emergencies]] for [[Jasper, Texas]] at 7:08 p.m. CDT and [[Fort Polk, Louisiana]] at 8:13 p.m. CDT. An EF2 tornado also passed just south of [[Alexandria, Louisiana]], damaging structures at [[Louisiana State University of Alexandria|LSU-Alexandria]], and killing one person east of [[Woodworth, Louisiana|Woodworth]] when a mobile home was destroyed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.katc.com/news/reports-lsua-buildings-damaged-by-severe-weather-wednesday-night|title=Reports: LSUA buildings damaged by severe weather Wednesday night|date=2020-04-23|website=KATC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/lsr/#LCH/202004230224/202004230224/0100 |title=LCH: 1 E Woodworth |date=2020-04-23 |access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> The system continued eastward into [[Mississippi]], [[Alabama]], [[Florida]], [[Georgia (U.S. State)|Georgia]] on April 23, producing additional tornadoes. An early morning EF2 significantly damaged airplane hangars near [[Bunkie, Louisiana]], while a massive EF2 wedge tornado mowed down hundreds of trees and destroyed half of a chicken house near [[Soso, Mississippi]], which had been devastated by [[2020 Easter tornado outbreak#Bassfield\u2013Soso\u2013Moss\u2013Pachuta, Mississippi|an EF4 tornado]] 11 days prior. Another large EF2 downed numerous trees, tore much of the roof off a house, and destroyed a metal building near [[McComb, Mississippi|McComb]]. Numerous tornadoes touched down in Florida later that day, most of which were weak. However, an EF2 tornado caused considerable damage near [[Marianna, Florida|Marianna]]. Overall, this outbreak produced 41 tornadoes and resulted in six fatalities.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Tornado]]\n** [[Tornadoes by year]]\n** [[Tornado records]]\n** [[Tornado climatology]]\n** [[Tornado myths]]\n* [[List of tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of F5 and EF5 tornadoes]]\n** [[List of North American tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of 21st-century Canadian tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of European tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in Asia]]\n** [[List of Southern Hemisphere tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes striking downtown areas]]\n* [[Tornado intensity]]\n** [[Fujita scale]]\n** [[Enhanced Fujita scale]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 tornado months}}\n{{2020 tornado outbreaks}}\n{{Tornadoes by year}}\n\n[[Category:2020 meteorology]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes of 2020]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists by year]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists]]\n[[Category:2020 natural disasters]]\n[[Category:2020-related lists|Torn]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Notable tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in 2020}}\n{{Infobox tornado year\n|name          = Tornadoes of 2020\n|image         = 2020 United States tornado count.png\n|caption       = A chart of the 2020 United States tornado count estimated from the number of preliminary reports\n|timespan      = January 3 \u2013 ongoing\n|max_EF        = EF4\n|max_location  = 5 different locations\n|max_date      = 4 different days\n|tornadoes_usa = 443\n|total_damages_usa = >$4.4&nbsp;billion\n|total_fatalities_world = 74\n|total_fatalities_usa = 74\n|year = 2020\n}}\n\nThis page documents notable [[tornado]]es and [[tornado outbreak]]s worldwide in '''2020'''. Strong and destructive tornadoes form most frequently in the [[United States]], [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], [[Bangladesh]], and [[East India|Eastern India]], but can occur almost anywhere under the right conditions. Tornadoes also develop occasionally in southern [[Canada]] during the [[Northern Hemisphere]]'s summer and somewhat regularly at other times of the year across [[Europe]], [[Asia]], [[Argentina]], [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]]. Tornadic events are often accompanied by other forms of [[severe weather]], including strong [[thunderstorm]]s, strong [[winds]], and [[hail]].\n\nThere have been 581 preliminary filtered reports of tornadoes in the United States in 2020,<ref>{{cite web |title=Annual Severe Weather Report Summary 2020 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/online/monthly/2020_annual_summary.html |publisher=Storm Prediction Center |accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref> of which at least 443 have been confirmed. Worldwide, 74 tornado-related deaths have been confirmed, all in the United States.\n\n==Events==\n{{Tornadoes of 2020/Deadly}}\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020|List of United States tornadoes in April 2020}}\n\n===United States yearly total===\n<!-- This section is transcluded to other articles; modify with caution. -->\n<onlyinclude>\n{{Tornado Chart\n|Total = 443\n|FU = 10\n|F0 = 131\n|F1 = 217\n|F2 = 65\n|F3 = 15\n|F4 = 5\n|F5 = 0\n| Enhanced=yes\n}}\n</onlyinclude>\n\n==January==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#January}}\nThere were 90 tornadoes reported in the United States in January, of which 88 were confirmed. Overall, January was an active month, with over twice the national average of 35 tornadoes.\n\n===January 3 (South Africa)===\nOn January 3, severe thunderstorms developed over the [[Mpumalanga]] province of [[South Africa]]. One thunderstorm developed into a supercell which produced an EF3 tornado that caused significant damage to a farm, destroyed the houses of seven families, and destroyed about {{convert|200|hectare|acre|sigfig=1}} of pine forest.<ref>{{cite web |title=Media Release: Panbult tornado (Mpumalanga) on the 3rd of January 2020. |url=https://twitter.com/SAWeatherServic/status/1214087467692941312?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1214087467692941312&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.news24.com%2FSouthAfrica%2FNews%2Fwatch-tornado-lasting-about-40-minutes-destroyed-farm-and-7-houses-in-mpumalanga-saws-confirms-20200106 |website=Twitter |publisher=South African Weather Service |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===January 10\u201311===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of January 10\u201311, 2020}}\n{{stack begin}}{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 25|EF1= 41|EF2= 13|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=0}}{{stack end}}\n[[File:Carollton EF2 damage1.jpg|thumb|left|High-end EF2 damage to a house near Carrollton, Alabama.]]\nOn January 10, the Storm Prediction Center issues a moderate risk of severe weather for much of the Southern United States, including a 15% hatched risk of tornadoes. A squall line of severe thunderstorms with numerous embedded circulations and semi-discrete supercell structures moved from [[Texas]] and [[Oklahoma]] to the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]], producing numerous tornadoes. A high-end EF2 tornado near [[Carrollton, Alabama]] destroyed multiple homes and mobile homes, and resulted in three fatalities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Three people killed in Pickens Co. tornado |url=https://www.wbrc.com/2020/01/11/three-people-killed-pickens-co-tornado/ |publisher=WBRC |accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Three people were fatally injured when a long-tracked EF2 tornado destroyed two mobile homes south of [[Haughton, Louisiana]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Enfinger |first1=Emily |title=87-year-old dies from injuries from Haughton tornado |url=https://eu.shreveporttimes.com/story/news/local/2020/01/15/third-death-confimred-haughton-tornado/4480014002/ |publisher=Shreveport Times |accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref> and an EF1 tornado killed one person near [[Nacogdoches, Texas]] when a large tree fell onto a mobile home.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brackett |first1=Ron |last2=Wesner Childs |first2=Jan |title=Tornadoes, Severe Storms Kill 8; More Than 300,000 Lose Power |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-01-11-severe-storms-tornadoes-impact-texas-louisiana-tennessee-arkansas-mississippi |website=weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=January 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Houston, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey for January 10 Burleson County Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSHGX&e=202001112109|date=January 11, 2020|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> An EF2 tornado struck [[Rome, Mississippi]], causing significant damage and destroying the local post office. An EF2 tornado also struck [[Union Grove, Alabama]], significantly damaging a school building in the community. Another school also sustained major damage near [[Kershaw, South Carolina]], as a result of another EF2 tornado. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 79 tornadoes, and resulted in 7 fatalities. Total damage from the event reached $1.1&nbsp;billion according to the [[National Centers for Environmental Information]].<ref name=\"NCEI_billion\">{{cite web|publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information|year=2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Billion-Dollar Weather and Climate Disasters: Events|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/billions/events}}</ref>\n\n==February==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#February}}\nThere were 51 tornadoes reported in the United States in February, of which 42 were confirmed. February was also an active month, besting the national average of 29 tornadoes.\n\n===February 5\u20137===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 21|EF2= 6|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=1}}\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of February 5\u20137, 2020}}\n[[File:KannapolisNCEF2-2020.jpg|thumb|left|EF2 damage to a house near Kannapolis, North Carolina.]]\nBeginning on February 5, a moderate tornado outbreak affected the Deep South and Eastern United States. On the first day of the outbreak, an EF2 tornado caused significant tree and outbuilding damage near [[Pickens, Mississippi]], and injured four people. A long-tracked EF2 tornado touched down near [[Bay Springs, Mississippi]] and passed though the town of [[Enterprise, Clarke County, Mississippi|Enterprise]], downing numerous trees and power poles and toppling a metal fire tower. This tornado tore large sections of roofing off of multiple homes in rural areas as well. On February 6, one person was killed in [[Marengo County, Alabama]] when an EF1 tornado destroyed a mobile home near [[Demopolis, Alabama|Demopolis]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/06/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202002070055|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Jackson, Mississippi|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/05/2020 \u2013 02/06/2020 Tornado Event \u2013 Update #1|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSJAN&e=202002070252|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref> An EF2 tornado also touched down near [[Kannapolis, North Carolina]], to the north of [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]]. No injuries were reported, though multiple homes were damaged, including one that lost its roof and some exterior walls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/06/tornado-touches-down-kannapolis/|title=Tornado touches down in Kannapolis|website=WBTV|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/confirmed-tornado-damages-homes-in-kannapolis/275-3a51f749-53cd-490f-bf2c-3fd08c8c793c|title=Confirmed tornado damages homes in the Kannapolis area|website=WCNC|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Tornado rips roof off home in Kannapolis, North Carolina|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gE8N-dBHI7k|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> Another EF2 downed metal truss transmission towers near [[Kings Mountain, North Carolina|Kings Mountain]], and an EF1 tornado caused damage in the southern suburbs of Charlotte.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://salisburypost.com/2020/02/08/three-rescued-from-flood-waters-weather-service-confirms-tornado-in-rowan-county/|title=As flooding, damage lingers, 3 rescued from Third Creek, weather service confirms tornadoes in Rowan|last=Walker|first=Shavonne|work=[[Salisbury Post]]|date=2020-02-08|accessdate=2020-02-08}}</ref><ref name=WBTV>{{cite news|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/07/nws-confirms-ef-tornado-near-pineville/|title=NWS confirms EF-1 tornado near Pineville|last=Myers|first=Jason|work=[[WBTV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/tornado-stanly-albemarle-damage-storm/275-227d0b28-9341-4b91-a7a0-057602e4a803|title=EF-1 tornado confirmed near Albemarle|work=[[WCNC-TV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> A high-end EF1 tornado moved directly through [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]] as well, causing considerable damage to homes and businesses.<ref name=WBTV/> On February 7, five tornadoes touched down in Maryland, including an EF1 that struck [[Westminster, Maryland|Westminster]] and [[Manchester, Maryland|Manchester]], causing moderate damage. An EF0 tornado also caused minor damage in [[Leesburg, Virginia]]. Along with the tornadic storms, heavy rainfall resulted in widespread flooding also occurred throughout the southern states. Total economic losses from the event exceeded $925&nbsp;million. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 37 tornadoes, and resulted in one fatality.<ref>{{cite report|publisher=Aon|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Global Catastrophe Recap: February 2020|url=http://thoughtleadership.aonbenfield.com/Documents/20200309_analytics-if-february-global-recap.pdf|page=4|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n==March==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#March}}\nThere were 106 tornadoes reported in the United States in March, of which 78 were confirmed. Although March was just about average in number of tornadoes, the series of severe weather outbreaks and tornadoes throughout March inflicted widespread damage across the country. Combined economic losses reached approximately $2.4&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|author=Matt Sheehan|publisher=Reinsurance News|date=April 14, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Separate billion-dollar events mark active month for US tornadoes: Aon|url=https://www.reinsurancene.ws/separate-billion-dollar-events-mark-active-month-for-us-tornadoes-aon/}}</ref>\n\n===March 2\u20133===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of March 2\u20133, 2020}}\n[[File:CookevilleTNEF4rubbleanddamage.jpg|thumb|left|EF4 damage in a residential area near Cookeville, Tennessee.]]\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 3|EF2= 4|EF3= 1|EF4= 1|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nA small but devastating tornado outbreak affected parts of the Southern United States on the evening of March 2 into the early morning hours of March 3, with the most severe damage and all fatalities occurring in Tennessee. [[Nashville, Tennessee]] was directly struck by a high-end EF3 tornado just after 12:30&nbsp;a.m. CDT on March 3. Major structural damage and six fatalities occurred as the tornado passed just north of downtown Nashville and through [[Mount Juliet, Tennessee|Mount Juliet]] to the east. Additional tornadoes were reported in [[Missouri]], [[Alabama]], [[Tennessee]], and [[Kentucky]]. An EF2 tornado killed one person and caused significant damage to homes, mobile homes, and outbuildings near [[Camden, Tennessee]] as well. The majority of the deaths occurred in Putnam County, where a violent EF4 tornado touched down near [[Baxter, Tennessee|Baxter]] shortly before 2:00&nbsp;a.m. and moved into western [[Cookeville, Tennessee|Cookeville]]. Many homes and other buildings were completely leveled or swept away in residential areas of Cookeville, and 19 people were killed in town.<ref name=\"OHX\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=March 2\u20133, 2020 Tornadoes and Severe Weather|url=https://www.weather.gov/ohx/20200303|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=March 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=21 killed, 221 hospitalized after tornadoes rip through Nashville, surrounding areas|url=https://www.abcactionnews.com/news/national/six-killed-at-least-20-hurt-after-tornadoes-rip-through-nashville-surrounding-areas|publisher=ABC Action News|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> In addition, two EF2 tornadoes also downed numerous trees in forested areas near [[Alvaton, Kentucky]] and [[Clarkrange, Tennessee]] as well. A lone, long-tracked [[supercell]] thunderstorm was responsible for all nine of the tornadoes in Tennessee as it moved from near [[Dyersburg, Tennessee|Dyersburg]] in West Tennessee to near [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] in East Tennessee. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 14 tornadoes, and resulted in 26 fatalities.<ref name=\"OHX\"/>\n\n===March 18\u201319===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 11|EF2= 5|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nOn March 18, an intense [[supercell thunderstorm]] spawned numerous weak tornadoes as it tracked through [[Jack County, Texas|Jack]], [[Stephens County, Texas|Stephens]], [[Wise County, Texas|Wise]], and [[Young County, Texas|Young counties]] in [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Fort Worth, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/18/2020 Tornado Event \u2013 Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSFWD&e=202003201858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> With severe storms continuing into the early morning hours of March 19, two EF2 tornadoes caused considerable damage to trees, vehicles, farming equipment, and outbuildings near [[Trent, Texas]].<ref name=\"SJT0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in San Angelo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event \u2013 Update #1|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSSJT&e=202003201627|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The thunderstorm responsible for those tornadoes went on to produce another EF2 tornado that damaged a large building and over 100 cars at a correctional facility northeast of [[Abilene, Texas|Abilene]]. Near [[Sweetwater, Texas|Sweetwater]], an EF2 tornado damaged or destroyed several wind turbines.<ref name=\"SJT0319\"/> Later that day, a large portion of the southern [[Great Plains]] was in line for severe storms, along with parts of the [[Ohio Valley]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Darrow|title=Mar 19, 2020 0100 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2020/day1otlk_20200319_0100.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> During the afternoon, a squall line with several embedded supercells formed from [[Oklahoma]] to [[Indiana]], producing tornadoes in [[Oklahoma]], [[Illinois]], and [[Arkansas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tulsa, Oklahoma|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTSA&e=202003210250|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PAH0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003202132|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"LZK0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornadoes Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003212158|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 21, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> A large EF2 tornado touched down near [[Everton, Arkansas]] before moving through the southeastern part of town, causing significant damage to homes, a school, outbuildings, and trees.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> Three EF1 tornadoes also touched down in Arkansas, one of which tracked between [[Gassville, Arkansas|Gassville]] and [[Mountain Home, Arkansas|Mountain Home]], inflicting considerable damage to some homes. Further north, two EF1 tornadoes caused damage in [[Sunfield, Illinois|Sunfield]] and [[Dahlgren, Illinois]].<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> One person was injured in Illinois,<ref name=\"PAH0319\"/> and another injury occurred in Arkansas. A total of 21 tornadoes were confirmed.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/>\n\n===March 28\u201329===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 3|EF1= 11|EF2= 2|EF3= 1|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 3}}\nOn March 28, the SPC issued a moderate risk of severe weather for much of Illinois, including a 15% hatched risk of tornadoes. An enhanced risk of severe weather was in place \nacross parts of Iowa, Missouri, Indiana, and Arkansas as well. Only weak tornadoes touched down in the moderate risk area, though a few strong tornadoes occurred elsewhere. A large EF3 tornado struck the city of [[Jonesboro, Arkansas]], while being streamed live on local news stations, producing major damage to homes, businesses, and a shopping mall. Vehicles were thrown and mangled, and the local airport sustained severe damage as well. A train was also derailed, and 22 injuries occurred in Jonesboro.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado flattens buildings in Jonesboro, Arkansas, as severe weather moves across the Midwest, Lower Mississippi River Valley |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/28/weather/tornadoes-severe-storms-forecast-saturday/index.html |website=CNN |publisher=CNN |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Damage Reported in Northeastern Arkansas as Tornado Strikes Jonesboro |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-03-28-severe-weather-tornado-impacts-plains-south-midwest |website=Weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"20200328 reports\">{{cite web |title=Today's Storm Reports (20200328 1200 UTC \u2013 20200329 1159 UTC) (Print Version) |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200328_rpts.html|website=NOAA |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Memphis, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMEG&e=202003292239|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Zoellner |first1=Danielle |title=Tornado rips through Arkansas town, injuring six people |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/arkansas-tornado-jonesboro-weather-injured-a9432511.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\nThe same storm that produced this tornado also produced two EF1 tornadoes, one before and one after it moved over Jonesboro.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003292104|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\"/>\nInto the evening, numerous weak tornadoes touched down in [[Iowa]] and [[Illinois]], and another in southwest [[Wisconsin]]. This included an EF1 tornado that caused moderate damage to apartment buildings and trees in [[Oelwein, Iowa]].<ref name=\"20200328 reports\"/>\nA low-end EF2 tornado moved through the southern fringes of [[Henderson, Kentucky]], destroying numerous outbuildings and a barn, and damaging dozens of homes and trees.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Henderson County KY Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300139|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\nAnother EF2 struck the town of [[Newburgh, Indiana]], where five homes sustained partial to total roof removal, and one home had a few upper floor exterior walls ripped off. Numerous other homes in town sustained less severe damage, and two people were injured in Newburgh.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Newburgh Indiana Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300138|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarly in the morning of March 29, the same storm system produced an EF0 tornado that mainly damaged trees near [[Sparta, Tennessee]]. Overall, this outbreak produced 20 tornadoes.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/29/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSOHX&e=202003311858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March 30\u201331===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 3|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 2}}\nOn the evening of March 30, isolated supercells developed across Texas and Oklahoma, producing two weak tornadoes. One of these was given an EFU rating, and the other, which was a [[landspout]] or non-mesocylonic tornado, was given an EF0 rating.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Amarillo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/30/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSAMA&e=202003312336|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> \nOn March 31, multiple supercells and embedded mesocyclones formed along and just ahead of a convective line, producing several tornadoes across parts of the [[Southeastern United States]].<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\">{{cite web |title=SPC Storm reports for03/31/20 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200331_rpts.html |publisher=Storm Prediction |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\nA high-end EF2 tornado caused significant damage just south of [[Eufaula, Alabama]], where multiple homes in a subdivision had their roofs torn off. A few of these homes sustained partial exterior wall loss.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fuentes |first1=Carmen |title=Eufaula tornado runs through neighborhood |url=https://www.wtvy.com/content/news/Eufaula-tornado-runs-through-neighborhood-569268011.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |agency=WTVY |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202004020401|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> Multiple other weak tornadoes were confirmed in southeast [[Mississippi]], southern [[Alabama]], and northern [[Florida]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee, Florida|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=202004032145|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 3, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\"/> A landspout tornado was caught on video around 2:30&nbsp;p.m. PDT at the north edge of [[Richland, Washington]], causing no damage. A total of 15 tornadoes are confirmed.<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\"/>\n\n==April==\n{{see also|List of United States tornadoes in April 2020}}\nThere have been 339 tornadoes reported in the United States this April, of which 236 have been confirmed.\n\n===April 7\u20139===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 20|EF1= 10|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nA few weak tornadoes touched down across [[Ohio]] and [[Pennsylvania]] late on April 7 and into the early morning of April 8, causing tree and structure damage. Later on the night of April 8, a large EF2 cone tornado touched down near [[Weiner, Arkansas]], completely destroying a mobile home. The tornado then struck [[Harrisburg, Arkansas]] in [[Poinsett County, Arkansas|Poinsett County]].<ref>https://twitter.com/nwsmemphis/status/1248334194377232384?s=21</ref><ref>https://media.arkansasonline.com/img/photos/2020/04/09/storm1_t800.jpg?90232451fbcadccc64a17de7521d859a8f88077d</ref> In Harrisburg, one frail home was completely leveled by the tornado, and several homes nearby were also badly damaged or destroyed in residential areas of town.<ref>https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2020/apr/09/forecasters-tornado-touched-down-overnight-northwe/#.Xo9c00N8lmQ.twitter</ref> Extensive tree damage occurred and two people were injured in Harrisburg.<ref>https://twitter.com/kwoodallTV/status/1248076374084124673?s=19</ref> Numerous tornadoes, all of which weak and short-lived, occurred across [[Indiana]], [[Kentucky]], and Ohio that night as well. One EF1 tornado caused considerable damage to a brick building in downtown [[Mooresville, Indiana]]. Another EF1 tornado damaged two mobile homes, a garage, and trees near [[Wilkesville, Ohio]] on April 9 before the outbreak came to an end. Numerous reports of damaging straight line winds were also received throughout the event. A total of 31 tornadoes were confirmed.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\n=== April 12\u201313 ===\n{{Tornado chart small|FU = 0|F0 = 29|F1 = 75|F2 = 20|F3 = 12|F4 = 3|F5 = 0|Enhanced=yes}}\n{{main|2020 Easter tornado outbreak}}\n[[File:Cantwell Mill, Mississippi, April 12, 2020, tornado damage.jpg|thumb|left|High-end EF4 damage to a large, well-anchored cabin northeast of Bassfield, Mississippi.]]\nOn the morning of April 12, the SPC issued a moderate risk of severe weather for much of the [[Southern United States]], including a 15% risk of tornadoes. From the late morning of April 12 through the early morning of April 13, a major and deadly tornado outbreak unfolded across the region, with many strong to violent tornadoes touching down and causing major damage and numerous fatalities. Over a 48 hour period from nighttime on April 11 to the evening of April 13, 139 tornadoes touched down from Texas to Maryland. This event was well forecasted, with the [[Storm Prediction Center]] issuing severe weather outlooks as early as five days before the outbreak. At 10:40 a.m. CDT on April 12, a [[Particularly Dangerous Situation]] [[Tornado Watch]] was issued by the Storm Prediction Center across northeast [[Louisiana]], southeast [[Arkansas]], and central and northern [[Mississippi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0106.html|title=PDS Watch 106|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 11:44 a.m. CDT, a [[Tornado emergency|tornado emergency]] was issued for [[Monroe, Louisiana]] as an [[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF3 tornado]] moved through the city, causing significant damage to more than 200 homes, as well as the [[Monroe Regional Airport (Louisiana)|Monroe Regional Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.magnoliareporter.com/news_and_business/regional_news/article_4f3bcd2e-7ce3-11ea-8412-1b0152c3f85d.html|title=Magnolia Reporter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado Emergency for Monroe Louisiana and Northeast Ouachita Parish |url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=SVSSHV&e=202004121644 |website=Iowa Environmental Mesonet |publisher=National Weather Service Forecast Office in Shreveport, Louisiana |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SteveWAFB/status/1249799061898760192?s=20|title=Steve Caparotta of WAFB on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 3:30 p.m. CDT, two back-to-back supercells produced three intense and long-tracked tornadoes in southern Mississippi, including two rated EF4. The violent tornadoes promted the [[National Weather Service]] in [[Jackson, Mississippi]] to issue multiple tornado emergencies for numerous towns. The first of these two EF4 tornadoes leveled and swept away homes near [[Sartinville, Mississippi]], killing four. The second one reached high-end EF4 strength as it completely debarked trees, lofted vehicles hundreds of yards through the air, and obliterated well-built homes and structures in and around the towns of [[Bassfield, Mississippi|Bassfield]], [[Soso, Mississippi|Soso]], and [[Moss, Mississippi|Moss]]. This high-end EF4 tornado killed eight people, and was the largest tornado ever recorded in Mississippi state history. At 4:40 p.m. CDT, a second [[Particularly Dangerous Situation|PDS watch]] was issued affecting extreme southeast Mississippi and most of [[Alabama]], including the cities of [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]], [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]], [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]], and [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0110.html|title=Storm Prediction Center \u2013 PDS Watch 110|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As the system progressed northeastward into the nighttime hours, another tornado emergency was issued, this time at 11:28 p.m. EDT for the towns of [[Ooltewah, Tennessee|Ooltewah]] and [[Collegedale, Tennessee|Collegedale]] as a deadly EF3 tornado struck the eastern suburbs of [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]], killing three and injuring 19.<ref>https://twitter.com/NWSMorristown/status/1249735208460419073?s=20</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMRX&e=202004151915|title=NWS Morristown Damage Survey|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> A deadly EF2 tornado also impacted the small community of [[Sumac, Georgia]], destroying several mobile homes and killing seven people.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\nDuring the early morning hours April 13, the storms that formed the day before congealed into a strong [[squall line]] as they advanced into eastern [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] and the [[Carolinas]]. Multiple embedded circulations and semi-discrete supercells within the line spawned numerous strong and deadly tornadoes across the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSCharlestonSC/status/1249652455073370113?s=20|title=NWS Charleston SC on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/StuOstro/status/1250057470669721602</ref> Ten tornadoes of EF3 or greater strength occurred on day two of the outbreak, including eight in [[South Carolina]], where nine tornado-related fatalities occurred. The most significant tornado that occurred on April 13 was a 3/4-mile wide EF4 in [[Hampton County, South Carolina]] that destroyed many homes and took the lives of five people near [[Estill, South Carolina|Estill]] and [[Nixville, South Carolina|Nixville]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSCHS&e=202004152035|title=NWS Charleston Damage Survey|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Another high-end EF3 struck [[Seneca, South Carolina]], destroying multiple homes and a manufacturing plant, killing one person.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\nWith <!-- do not change this unless the fatality count has updated -->32<!-- as of April 20, only 32 fatalities have been confirmed to be tornado-related --> tornado-related fatalities, it was the deadliest outbreak since <!-- again, do not change to 2012 unless the TORNADO-RELATED fatality count exceeds 35 -->[[Tornado outbreak of April 27\u201330, 2014|April 27\u201330, 2014]].<ref>{{cite web |title=At Least 41 People Have Died After a Tornado Outbreak Ravaged the South |url=https://time.com/5820741/deadly-tornadoes-storms-south/ |website=TIME USA |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April 19\u201320===\n{{Tornado chart small|FU = 0|F0 = 5|F1 = 11|F2 = 3|F3 = 0|F4 = 1|F5 = 0|Enhanced=yes}}\nFor the second straight Sunday and Monday, several strong to violent tornadoes touched down across the Southern United States. On April 19, the SPC issued a moderate risk of severe weather for much of the Deep South, including a 15% hatched risk of tornadoes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Today's Storm Reports (20200419 1200 UTC \u2013 20200420 1159 UTC)|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200419_rpts.html|website=NOAA |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Later that evening, a large, violent EF4 tornado moved through  or near the rural Mississippi communities of [[Hurricane Creek, Mississippi|Hurricane Creek]], [[Sandy Hook, Mississippi|Sandy Hook]], [[Pine Burr, Mississippi|Pine Burr]], and areas north of [[Purvis, Mississippi]], killing one person and injuring another. A well-built house was leveled by this tornado, and numerous other homes and mobile homes were damaged or destroyed as well. Numerous trees were also snapped and partially debarked along the path.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in New Orleans|title=NWS New Orleans Tornado Report|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=LSRLIX&e=202004201907|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSJacksonMS/status/1252400542443122691|title=The Hurricane Creek/Pine Burr/Purvis/Camp Shelby tornado has been rated an EF-4 with estimated maximum wind of 170 MPH, path length of 54.2 miles, and maximum path width of 1.25 miles. Additional details will follow later this evening.|last=Jackson MS|first=NWS|date=2020-04-20|website=@NWSJacksonMS|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Later that evening, an EF2 tornado caused severe damage to a duplex, a home, some chicken houses, and other structures near [[Andalusia, Alabama]], injuring one person.<ref>{{cite web|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Mobile, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey for April 19, 2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMOB&e=202004212319|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> An EF1 tornado caused damage to multiple mobile homes and destroyed an RV camper near [[Robertsdale, Alabama]] as well, causing another injury.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMOB&e=202004210100|title=IEM :: PNS from NWS MOB|last=akrherz@iastate.edu|first=daryl herzmann|website=mesonet.agron.iastate.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> An EF2 tornado also struck the small community of [[Tumbleton, Alabama]], tearing the roofs off of some homes and a business, and causing one fatality when a mobile home was destroyed.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\nEarly on April 20, another EF2 tornado heavily damaged several homes and a mobile home near [[Bridgeboro, Georgia]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee FL|title=NWS Tallahassee FL Damage Survey|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=202004211628|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> Later on, several more tornadoes were reported throughout the morning into the afternoon in Central Florida.<ref>{{cite web|title=Today's Storm Reports (20200420 1200 UTC \u2013 20200421 1159 UTC)|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200420_rpts.html|website=NOAA |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> An EF0 tornado caused considerable damage to mobile homes and businesses in [[Homosassa, Florida|Homosassa]] and [[Homosassa Springs, Florida]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tampa Bay Ruskin FL|title=NWS Tampa Bay Ruskin FL Damage Survey|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTBW&e=202004201854|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chronicleonline.com/news/local/nws-tornado-causes-damage-in-homosassa-power-out-for-more-than-1-000-customers/article_ca25601c-831a-11ea-9981-a3a03237cc85.html|title=NWS: Tornado causes damage in Homosassa; power out for more than 1,000 customers|last=Thompson|first=Jeff Bryan & Buster|website=Chronicle Online|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Another EF0 tornado was caught on video lifting a stationary construction trailer across [[Interstate 75 in Florida|Interstate 75]] in [[Wildwood, Florida]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/PaulFox13/status/1252257783912824832|title=That'll stop traffic. Line of strong to severe thunderstorms across central #Florida produced this potential #tornado in Citrus county on I-75. #Skytower|last=DellegattoHigh voltage signFOX|first=Paul|date=2020-04-20|website=@PaulFox13|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsbreak.com/news/0OoG9ZmK/suspected-tornado-crosses-interstate-as-severe-weather-hits-central-florida|title=Suspected Tornado Crosses Interstate as Severe Weather Hits Central Florida|website=News Break|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> A total of 20 tornadoes were confirmed as a result of this outbreak, which resulted in two fatalities.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\n===April 22\u201323===\n{{Tornado chart small|FU = 0|F0 = 10|F1 = 21|F2 = 9|F3 = 1|F4 = 0|F5 = 0|Enhanced=yes}}\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of April 22\u201323, 2020}} \n[[File:MadillOklahoma-2020EF2damage.jpg|thumb|left|EF2 damage to a manufacturing facility in Madill, Oklahoma.]]\nOn the morning of April 22, the SPC issued an enhanced risk of severe weather for parts of Oklahoma, Texas, Louisiana, and Arkansas, which included a 10% hatched risk of tornadoes. Later that evening, multiple supercell thunderstorms developed and several tornadoes struck southern [[Oklahoma]] east of [[Interstate 35|I-35]], including a high-end EF2 tornado that killed two people and injured at least 30 others in [[Madill, Oklahoma|Madill]]. Industrial buildings were severely damaged at two manufacturing facilities in Madill, while a few homes and mobile homes in town were damaged or destroyed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Two people killed after tornado hits Marshall County, officials say |url=https://www.koco.com/article/person-killed-after-tornado-hits-marshall-county-officials-say/32243168 |accessdate=23 April 2020 |agency=KOCO News 5 |date=22 April 2020}}</ref> Several EF1 tornadoes also caused damage to homes, outbuildings, and trees near [[Wapanucka, Oklahoma|Wapanucka]], [[Pauls Valley, Oklahoma|Pauls Valley]], and [[Armstrong, Oklahoma|Armstrong]]. A deadly EF3 wedge tornado moved through [[San Jacinto County, Texas|San Jacinto]] and [[Polk County, Texas]] around 6:00 p.m. CDT, leaving three dead and causing severe damage in [[Onalaska, Texas|Onalaska]] and [[Seven Oaks, Texas|Seven Oaks]]. Numerous homes and mobile homes were damaged or destroyed along the path of this tornado, and 33 others were injured.<ref>https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200422_rpts.html</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSHouston/status/1253463558257471488?s=20|title=NWS Houston on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The same cell warranted [[tornado emergency|tornado emergencies]] for [[Jasper, Texas]] at 7:08 p.m. CDT and [[Fort Polk, Louisiana]] at 8:13 p.m. CDT. An EF2 tornado also passed just south of [[Alexandria, Louisiana]], damaging structures at [[Louisiana State University of Alexandria|LSU-Alexandria]], and killing one person east of [[Woodworth, Louisiana|Woodworth]] when a mobile home was destroyed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.katc.com/news/reports-lsua-buildings-damaged-by-severe-weather-wednesday-night|title=Reports: LSUA buildings damaged by severe weather Wednesday night|date=2020-04-23|website=KATC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/lsr/#LCH/202004230224/202004230224/0100 |title=LCH: 1 E Woodworth |date=2020-04-23 |access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> The system continued eastward into [[Mississippi]], [[Alabama]], [[Florida]], [[Georgia (U.S. State)|Georgia]] on April 23, producing additional tornadoes. An early morning EF2 significantly damaged airplane hangars near [[Bunkie, Louisiana]], while a massive EF2 wedge tornado mowed down hundreds of trees and destroyed half of a chicken house near [[Soso, Mississippi]], which had been devastated by [[2020 Easter tornado outbreak#Bassfield\u2013Soso\u2013Moss\u2013Pachuta, Mississippi|an EF4 tornado]] 11 days prior. Another large EF2 downed numerous trees, tore much of the roof off a house, and destroyed a metal building near [[McComb, Mississippi|McComb]]. Numerous tornadoes touched down in Florida later that day, most of which were weak. However, an EF2 tornado caused considerable damage near [[Marianna, Florida|Marianna]]. Overall, this outbreak produced 41 tornadoes and resulted in six fatalities.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Tornado]]\n** [[Tornadoes by year]]\n** [[Tornado records]]\n** [[Tornado climatology]]\n** [[Tornado myths]]\n* [[List of tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of F5 and EF5 tornadoes]]\n** [[List of North American tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of 21st-century Canadian tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of European tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in Asia]]\n** [[List of Southern Hemisphere tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes striking downtown areas]]\n* [[Tornado intensity]]\n** [[Fujita scale]]\n** [[Enhanced Fujita scale]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 tornado months}}\n{{2020 tornado outbreaks}}\n{{Tornadoes by year}}\n\n[[Category:2020 meteorology]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes of 2020]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists by year]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists]]\n[[Category:2020 natural disasters]]\n[[Category:2020-related lists|Torn]]\n", "name_user": "ChessEric", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update totals.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tornadoes_of_2020"}
{"title_page": "Flying Without Wings", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name        = Flying Without Wings\n| cover       = 3FlyingWithoutWings2.jpg\n| alt         =\n| caption     = One of European artwork\n| type        = single\n| artist      = [[Westlife]]\n| album       = [[Westlife (album)|Westlife]] and [[Pok\u00e9mon: The Movie 2000]] soundtrack\n| released    = {{Start date|1999|10|18|df=y}}\n| format      = [[CD single]]\n| recorded    = Rokstone Studios, London\n| studio      =\n| venue       =\n| genre       = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length      = {{Duration|m=3|s=36}}\n| label       = [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]]\n| writer      =\n*[[Wayne Hector]]\n*[[Steve Mac]]\n| producer    = Steve Mac\n| prev_title  = [[If I Let You Go]]\n| prev_year   = 1999\n| next_title  = [[I Have a Dream (song)#Westlife version|I Have a Dream]]\n| next_title2 = [[Seasons in the Sun]]\n| next_year   = 1999\n| misc        = {{External music video|{{YouTube|fZOW8ZuLG2o|\"Flying Without Wings\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Flying Without Wings'''\" is a song by Irish [[boy band]] [[Westlife]] and it was released on 18 October 1999 as the third single from their [[Westlife (album)|self-titled debut studio album]]. It is the band's third most streamed song, and their fourth best selling single of all-time on both paid-for and combined sales categories in the [[United Kingdom]] as of January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/music/charts/official-uk-countdowns/westlife-official-top-20#37363 |title=Westlife &#124; Official Top 20|publisher=MTV |date= |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref><ref name=\"Westlife sales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/westlifes-top-20-biggest-songs-on-the-official-charts__25303/|title=Westlife's Top 20 biggest songs on the Official Charts|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=January 12, 2019|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref> \n\n==Background==\nThe song was written by [[Wayne Hector]] and [[Steve Mac]]. In an interview with [[HitQuarters]], Hector said the basic idea for the song came to him while on a break from working on a [[hip hop]] session with Ezi Cut in [[Los Angeles]]: <blockquote>I came up with a couple of lines for the first verse and then phoned my mama's house, left it on the answering machine, and said, \u201cDon't get rid of this!\u201d<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\">[http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview/opar/intrview_Wayne_Hector_Interview.html \"Interview With Wayne Hector\"], ''[[HitQuarters]]'', 1 Feb 2010.</ref></blockquote> Upon returning to England, Hector went into the studio to work on the idea with long-time songwriting partner and producer Steve Mac.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\"/> When the two discussed what the song was about they agreed that \"this is about our wives. This is about the things that make our lives complete.\"<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\"/> According to Hector the lyrics were completed in about half an hour.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\"/> He added, \"Flying Without Wings was a life-changing moment, and a song he says he is particularly proud of. A big moment for me was when Flying Without Wings came out, I\u2019d had a few Number 1s at that point, but that convinced people I could write good pop songs. After that, I started working with bigger acts and over a more diverse range of genres, including country and rock, which helped me pick up some credibility.\" The band's manager later revealed the song had been planned as the first solo single for [[Boyzone]]'s [[Stephen Gately]]. \"Stephen did the demo and he thought it was going to be his song,\" Walsh recalls. \"I'll be quite honest, I missed it, but as soon as [[Simon Cowell|Simon]] heard it he just went bananas. It was really difficult because Westlife were on tour with Boyzone, as the support act.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/jun/20/westlife-bow-out-ballad-career|title=Westlife bow out after 15-year ballad career based on hit formula|first=Peter|last=Robinson|date=20 June 2012|website=the Guardian}}</ref> \n\nIn a documentary aired on [[UTV (TV channel)|UTV]] called ''Westlife Back Home'', band member Shane Filan said it is probably the best song of their career, while former [[Taoiseach]] [[Bertie Ahern]] (band member [[Nicky Byrne]]'s father-in-law) revealed it is his favourite tune from the chart-topping band. The song also won the band their first of four ''[[The Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]'' prizes on the annual televised [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] music awards on 11 December 1999, scoring a total of 159,590 votes to beat Boyzone's [[Ronan Keating]] to the title.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/560705.stm|title=Westlife win song award|date=12 December 1999|website=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Official Charts Company]] stated, \"Flying Without Wings wasn't the first boyband ballad, nor is it the biggest selling, but it was certainly influential. After Flying Without Wings, what self-respecting boyband would dare stay seated on a stool for a key change? Stand, boys! Flying Without Wings has soundtracked births, proposals, marriages, funerals, and untold TV talent show montages over the last two decades.\"\n\n==Commercial performance==\nThe song became the group's third UK number-one single, spending 13 weeks on charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/artist/_/WESTLIFE/|title=WESTLIFE &#124; Artist|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=2012-01-06|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628173502/http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/westlife/|archivedate=2012-06-28}}</ref> It is also one of Westlife's biggest selling singles. The song is the group's first single to received a Gold sales certification in the UK for over 400,000 copies sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/music/charts/official-uk-countdowns/westlife-official-top-20#37363 |title=Westlife &#124; Official Top 20 &#124; MTV UK |publisher=Mtv.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-01-06}}</ref> As of October 2019, [[Official Charts Company]] stated that the single have 316,000 physical sales, 171,000 downloads, and 16 million streams in the UK alone so far.\n\n==Track listing==\n* '''United Kingdom'''\n; CD1\n# \"Flying Without Wings\" - 3:35\n# \"Everybody Knows\" - 3:45\n# \"Flying Without Wings\" (Video) - 3:40\n\n; CD2\n# \"Flying Without Wings\" - 3:35\n# \"That's What It's All About\" - 3:20\n# \"Flying Without Wings\" <small>(Acappella)</small> - 3:29\n* '''Australia'''\n# \"Flying Without Wings\" - 3:35\n# \"I Have a Dream\" (Remix) - 4:06\n# \"Seasons in the Sun\" (Single Remix) - 4:10\n# \"Flying Without Wings\" (Video) - 3:40\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Charts (1999/2000/2018)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|31|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings|note=Triple A-side with \"[[I Have a Dream (song)#Westlife version|I Have a Dream]]\" and \"[[Seasons in the Sun]]\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|7|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia Tip|8|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Denmark|Danish]] Airplay Chart\n|align=\"center\"|45\n|-\n{{singlechart|Denmark|14|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|19|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings|note=Double A-side with \"I Have a Dream\"}}\n|-\n|Europe ([[Eurochart Hot 100]])<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_fAgEAAAAMBAJ|quote=westlife.|title=Billboard|first=Nielsen Business Media|last=Inc|date=13 November 1999|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n{{singlechart|Finland|17|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|85|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings|songid=56881|accessdate=3 March 2020}}\n|-\n|Ireland ([[Irish Singles Chart|IRMA]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n{{singlechart|Norway|7|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|6|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Scotland|2|date=1999-10-24}}\n|-\n|[[Gaon Digital Chart|South Korea (Gaon Weekly BGM Chart)]]<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/chart/digital.php \n |title=Gaon Weekly BGM Chart \n |work=Gaon Chart \n |publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association \n |accessdate=July 5, 2019 \n |language=Korean \n |df=mdy \n}}\n*{{cite web\n |url=http://mobile.gaonchart.co.kr/searchList.gaon?serviceGbn=S1060&nationGbn=T&yyyy=2019&condition=2&search_str=Flying Without Wings\n |title=Flying Without Wings\n |date=July 5, 2019\n |archivedate=July 5, 2019 \n}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center\" |72\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|12|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|1|artist=Westlife|artistid=7712}}\n|-\n|UK Radio Airplay Chart\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Charts (2000)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|UK Singles ([[UK Singles Chart|Official Charts Company]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|67\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Charts (2008)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|UK Singles ([[UK Singles Chart|Official Charts Company]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zobbel.de/cluk/CLUK2008.HTM |title=Chart Log (2008) |work=zobbel.de/ |date=2008-12-27 |accessdate=2014-07-12}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|165\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Charts (2011)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|UK Singles ([[UK Singles Chart|Official Charts Company]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zobbel.de/cluk/CLUK2011.HTM |title=Chart Log (2011) |work=zobbel.de/ |date=2011-11-19 |accessdate=2014-07-12}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|172\n|}\n\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (2000)\n!Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|New Zealand (Recorded Music NZ)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/index.php/chart/?chart=4107|title=End of Year Charts 2000|publisher=Recorded Music NZ|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|43\n|}\n\n===Certifications and sales===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Sweden|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=1999|certyear=2001|accessdate=30 November 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=single|artist=Westlife|title=Flying Without Wings|award=Platinum|relyear=1999|certyear=2019|accessdate=1 March 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=true|streaming=true}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Duets==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Flying Without Wings\n| cover      = Westlifeboa.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = promo\n| artist     = [[Westlife]] featuring [[BoA]]\n| album      = [[Unbreakable: The Greatest Hits Volume 1]] (Asian edition), [[Shine We Are!]] and [[Next World]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2003}} (Asia)\n| format     = [[CD single]]\n| recorded   = 2002\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=36}}\n| label      = \n*[[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]]\n*[[S.M. Entertainment]]\n| writer     = \n*[[Wayne Hector]]\n*[[Steve Mac]]\n| producer   = \n*[[Lee Soo Man]]\n*Steve Mac\n| chronology = [[BoA]] singles\n| prev_track =\n| track_no   =\n| next_track =\n| misc        = {{External music video|{{YouTube|T1W8fWzfMk|\"Flying Without Wings (featuring BoA)\"}}}}\n}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Flying Without Wings\n| cover      = Westlife feat. Cristian Castro - Flying Without Wings.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = promo\n| artist     = [[Westlife]] featuring [[Cristian Castro]]\n| album      = [[Unbreakable: The Greatest Hits Volume 1]] (Spanish/Mexican edition)\n| released   = {{Start date|2002}} (Mexico)\n| format     = [[CD single]], digital download\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=36}}\n| label      =\n| writer     = \n*[[Wayne Hector]]\n*[[Steve Mac]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_track =\n| track_no   =\n| next_track =\n| misc        = {{External music video|{{YouTube|fZOW8ZuLG2o|\"Flying Without Wings (featuring Cristian Castro)\"}}}}\n}}\n\nIn 2002, as part of the promotion of their album ''[[Unbreakable: The Greatest Hits Volume 1]]'', the song was re-recorded as a [[duet]] with [[Mexico|Mexican]] singer [[Cristian Castro]] and [[South Korea]]n pop singer, [[BoA]]. Each duet was included on the Spanish & Asian editions of the album. Both duets were also released as singles in their two respective regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=239371 |title=Westlife Flying Without Wings Mexico Promo 5\" CD SINGLE (239371) |publisher=Eil.com |date=2003-03-12 |accessdate=2012-01-06}}</ref>\n\n===Track listing===\n* '''Mexico'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=244450 |title=Westlife Flying Without Wings Mexico 5\" CD SINGLE (244450) |publisher=Eil.com |date=2003-04-24 |accessdate=2012-01-06}}</ref>\n# \"Flying Without Wings\" <small>(Duet with Cristian Castro)</small> - 3:35\n# \"Never Knew I Was Losing You\" - 4:09\n* '''Asia'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=255411 |title=Westlife Flying Without Wings Japan Promo 5\" CD SINGLE (255411) |publisher=Eil.com |date=2003-08-15 |accessdate=2012-01-06}}</ref>\n# \"Flying Without Wings\" <small>(Duet with BoA)</small> - 3:35\n# \"Never Knew I Was Losing You\" - 4:09\n\n==Live version==\nIn 2004, as part of the promotion for their ''[[Turnaround Tour]]'', the band released the live version of the song. It was recorded during their tour in [[Ericsson Globe|Stockholm Globe Arena]]. Their live version peaked at number one in UK Singles Chart and was the first ever number one in the UK downloads chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/3617020.stm|title=Westlife top first download chart|date=1 September 2004|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Track listing===\n* '''UK'''\n# \"Flying Without Wings\" (Live)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westlife.com/global/discography/all/all/all/flying_without_wings_live#flash-nav|title=Westlife|website=www.westlife.com}}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Chart performance===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Charts (2004)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|UK Download Singles ([[UK Singles Chart|Official Charts Company]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|}\n\n==Video album==\nA karaoke version of \"Flying Without Wings\" was released on DVD in 2000 and debuted at number one. It includes easy to read lyrics, photographs & interactive menus, picture sleeve. It has a running time of 45 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=246048 |title=Westlife Flying Without Wings Karaoke UK DIGITAL VERSATILE DISC (246048) |publisher=Eil.com |date=2003-05-07 |accessdate=2012-01-06}}</ref>\n\n===Track listing===\n# \"Swear It Again\"\n# \"If I Let You Go\"\n# \"Flying Without Wings\"\n# \"Fool Again\"\n# \"Seasons in the Sun\"\n# \"I Have a Dream\"\n# \"More Than Words\"\n# \"Against All Odds\"\n\n===CD production===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"|width=100%\n|-\n|<small>Arranged by (strings)</small>\n|<small>: ''[[Richard Niles]]''</small>\n|-\n|<small>Arranged by (vocals)</small>\n|<small>: ''[[Steve Mac]], [[Wayne Hector]]''</small>\n|-\n|<small>Arranged by, mixed by</small>\n|<small>: ''Steve Mac''</small>\n|-\n|<small>Artwork by (design)</small>\n|<small>: ''Root''</small>\n|-\n|<small>Photography</small>\n|<small>: ''Brian Aris''</small>\n|-\n|<small>Bass guitar</small>\n|<small>: ''Steve Pearce''</small>\n|-\n|<small>Guitar</small>\n|<small>: ''Paul Gendler''</small>\n|-\n|<small>Performer (Choir Md)</small>\n|<small>: ''Benny Diggs''</small>\n|-\n|<small>Engineer (Mix)</small>\n|<small>: ''Matt Howe''</small>\n|-\n|<small>Engineer, Programmed by</small>\n|<small>: ''Chris Laws''</small>\n|-\n|<small>Other (management)</small>\n|<small>: ''[[Louis Walsh]], [[Ronan Keating]]''</small>\n|}\n\n==Tours performed at==\n*[[Where Dreams Come True Tour]] (2001)\n*[[World of Our Own Tour]] (2002)\n*[[Unbreakable Tour (Westlife concert tour)|Unbreakable Tour]] (2003)\n*[[Turnaround Tour]] (2004)\n*[[Number Ones Tour (Westlife concert tour)|The Number Ones Tour]] (2005)\n*[[Face to Face Tour]] (2006)\n*[[The Love Tour (Westlife concert tour)|The Love Tour]] (2007)\n*[[Back Home Tour]] (2008)\n*[[Where We Are Tour (Westlife)|Where We Are Tour]] (2010)\n*[[Gravity Tour]] (2011)\n*[[Greatest Hits Tour (Westlife)|Greatest Hits Tour]] (2012)\n*[[Shane Filan#Tours|You and Me Tour]] ([[Shane Filan]]) (2014)\n*Boyzlife Tour (Boyzlife) (2017)\n*[[The Twenty Tour]] (2019)\n\n==Other appearances==\nThe Westlife song has appeared in the 2000 [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] film ''[[Pok\u00e9mon: The Movie 2000]]'' as the final song of the credits in the film and on the official movie soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/album/original-soundtrack/pokemon-2000-the-power-of-one/435355 |title=Pokemon 2000: The Power of One- Original Soundtrack;|publisher=Billboard.com|date= |accessdate=2012-03-13}}</ref> It is also the only Westlife song that coincidently coincided with the original Japanese release date of the ''Pok\u00e9mon'' movie sequel. It also featured in the 2000 Australian film ''[[The Magic Pudding (film)|The Magic Pudding]]'' and 2000 French film ''[[Archibald the Koala|Archibald the Koala: The Movie]]''.\n\nOn 12 May 2018, the song was performed on Korean music programme '[[Immortal Songs 2]]' by [[Ali (South Korean singer)|Ali]] who placed second place that night. Band member [[Shane Filan]] was the featured 'Legend' and judged the participants.\n\n==Ruben Studdard version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Flying Without Wings\n| cover      = FlyingWithoutWings.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Ruben Studdard]]\n| album      =\n| released   = {{start date|2003|6|10|df=y}}\n| format     = [[CD single]]\n| recorded   = 2003\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = \n*[[Urban contemporary]]\n*[[contemporary R&B]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[J Records|J]]\n| writer     = \n*[[Wayne Hector]]\n*[[Steve Mac]]\n| producer   = \n*[[The Underdogs (duo)|The Underdogs]]\n*Face\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Superstar (Delaney and Bonnie song)#Ruben Studdard version|Superstar]]\n| next_year  = 2003\n}}\n\n\"Flying Without Wings\" was covered by ''[[American Idol]]'' winner [[Ruben Studdard]] as his debut single in 2003.  The single was released on June 10 and charted at number two on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] on June 28, behind  \"[[This Is the Night (Clay Aiken song)|This Is the Night]]\" by [[Clay Aiken]]. \"Flying Without Wings\" also gained attention on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles & Tracks]] chart, peaking at number thirteen, while it reached number 27 on the adult contemporary chart. It was also released in [[New Zealand]] and reached number two behind Clay Aiken. The single had sold 751,000 copies through December 2006. This version of the song also appears on the game [[Karaoke Revolution|Karaoke Revolution Presents: American Idol]].\n\n===Track listing===\n# \"Flying Without Wings\" the love you can see the same time as the first time in the future and the other is a great way to get the best out of the way and I have to say that I am not a fan of the most important thing to do is to provide an opportunity to make 88798lonu\n# \"[[Superstar (Delaney and Bonnie song)|Superstar]]\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{YouTube|G1LEISP6e9c|\"Flying Without Wings\" - Westlife Official Music Video}}\n*{{YouTube|-T1W8fWzfMk|\"Flying Without Wings\" - Westlife with BoA Official Music Video}}\n*{{YouTube|0udkZKyRAwY|\"Flying Without Wings\" - Westlife with Cristian Castro Official Music Video}}\n*{{YouTube|ZgiX33AVqA8|\"Flying Without Wings\" - Ruben Studdard Official Music Video}}\n*[http://www.westlife.com Official Westlife website]\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Westlife songs}}\n{{Ruben Studdard}}\n{{American Idol}}\n{{American Idol 2}}\n{{BoA singles}}\n{{Cristian Castro}}\n{{Pok\u00e9mon movie summary}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:1990s ballads]]\n[[Category:1999 singles]]\n[[Category:2003 singles]]\n[[Category:Westlife songs]]\n[[Category:Ruben Studdard songs]]\n[[Category:Delta Goodrem songs]]\n[[Category:BoA songs]]\n[[Category:Cristian Castro songs]]\n[[Category:Pop ballads]]\n[[Category:UK Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Irish Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Steve Mac]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Wayne Hector]]\n[[Category:Songs written for animated films]]\n[[Category:Songs from Pok\u00e9mon]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Steve Mac]]\n[[Category:1999 songs]]\n[[Category:RCA Records singles]]\n[[Category:Sony BMG singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name        = Flying Without Wings\n| cover       = 3FlyingWithoutWings2.jpg\n| alt         =\n| caption     = One of European artwork\n| type        = single\n| artist      = [[Westlife]]\n| album       = [[Westlife (album)|Westlife]] and [[Pok\u00e9mon: The Movie 2000]] soundtrack\n| released    = {{Start date|1999|10|18|df=y}}\n| format      = [[CD single]]\n| recorded    = Rokstone Studios, London\n| studio      =\n| venue       =\n| genre       = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length      = {{Duration|m=3|s=36}}\n| label       = [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]]\n| writer      =\n*[[Wayne Hector]]\n*[[Steve Mac]]\n| producer    = Steve Mac\n| prev_title  = [[If I Let You Go]]\n| prev_year   = 1999\n| next_title  = [[I Have a Dream (song)#Westlife version|I Have a Dream]]\n| next_title2 = [[Seasons in the Sun]]\n| next_year   = 1999\n| misc        = {{External music video|{{YouTube|fZOW8ZuLG2o|\"Flying Without Wings\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Flying Without Wings'''\" is a song by Irish [[boy band]] [[Westlife]] and it was released on 18 October 1999 as the third single from their [[Westlife (album)|self-titled debut studio album]]. It is the band's third most streamed song, and their fourth best selling single of all-time on both paid-for and combined sales categories in the [[United Kingdom]] as of January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/music/charts/official-uk-countdowns/westlife-official-top-20#37363 |title=Westlife &#124; Official Top 20|publisher=MTV |date= |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref><ref name=\"Westlife sales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/westlifes-top-20-biggest-songs-on-the-official-charts__25303/|title=Westlife's Top 20 biggest songs on the Official Charts|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=January 12, 2019|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref> \n\n==Background==\nThe song was written by [[Wayne Hector]] and [[Steve Mac]]. In an interview with [[HitQuarters]], Hector said the basic idea for the song came to him while on a break from working on a [[hip hop]] session with Ezi Cut in [[Los Angeles]]: <blockquote>I came up with a couple of lines for the first verse and then phoned my mama's house, left it on the answering machine, and said, \u201cDon't get rid of this!\u201d<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\">[http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview/opar/intrview_Wayne_Hector_Interview.html \"Interview With Wayne Hector\"], ''[[HitQuarters]]'', 1 Feb 2010.</ref></blockquote> Upon returning to England, Hector went into the studio to work on the idea with long-time songwriting partner and producer Steve Mac.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\"/> When the two discussed what the song was about they agreed that \"this is about our wives. This is about the things that make our lives complete.\"<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\"/> According to Hector the lyrics were completed in about half an hour.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\"/> He added, \"Flying Without Wings was a life-changing moment, and a song he says he is particularly proud of. A big moment for me was when Flying Without Wings came out, I\u2019d had a few Number 1s at that point, but that convinced people I could write good pop songs. After that, I started working with bigger acts and over a more diverse range of genres, including country and rock, which helped me pick up some credibility.\" The band's manager later revealed the song had been planned as the first solo single for [[Boyzone]]'s [[Stephen Gately]]. \"Stephen did the demo and he thought it was going to be his song,\" Walsh recalls. \"I'll be quite honest, I missed it, but as soon as [[Simon Cowell|Simon]] heard it he just went bananas. It was really difficult because Westlife were on tour with Boyzone, as the support act.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/jun/20/westlife-bow-out-ballad-career|title=Westlife bow out after 15-year ballad career based on hit formula|first=Peter|last=Robinson|date=20 June 2012|website=the Guardian}}</ref> \n\nIn a documentary aired on [[UTV (TV channel)|UTV]] called ''Westlife Back Home'', band member Shane Filan said it is probably the best song of their career, while former [[Taoiseach]] [[Bertie Ahern]] (band member [[Nicky Byrne]]'s father-in-law) revealed it is his favourite tune from the chart-topping band. The song also won the band their first of four ''[[The Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]'' prizes on the annual televised [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] music awards on 11 December 1999, scoring a total of 159,590 votes to beat Boyzone's [[Ronan Keating]] to the title.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/560705.stm|title=Westlife win song award|date=12 December 1999|website=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Official Charts Company]] stated, \"Flying Without Wings wasn't the first boyband ballad, nor is it the biggest selling, but it was certainly influential. After Flying Without Wings, what self-respecting boyband would dare stay seated on a stool for a key change? Stand, boys! Flying Without Wings has soundtracked births, proposals, marriages, funerals, and untold TV talent show montages over the last two decades.\"\n\n==Commercial performance==\nThe song became the group's third UK number-one single, spending 13 weeks on charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/artist/_/WESTLIFE/|title=WESTLIFE &#124; Artist|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=2012-01-06|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628173502/http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/westlife/|archivedate=2012-06-28}}</ref> It is also one of Westlife's biggest selling singles. The song is the group's first single to received a Gold sales certification in the UK for over 400,000 copies sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/music/charts/official-uk-countdowns/westlife-official-top-20#37363 |title=Westlife &#124; Official Top 20 &#124; MTV UK |publisher=Mtv.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-01-06}}</ref> As of October 2019, [[Official Charts Company]] stated that the single have 316,000 physical sales, 171,000 downloads, and 16 million streams in the UK alone so far.\n\n==Track listing==\n* '''United Kingdom'''\n; CD1\n# \"Flying Without Wings\" - 3:35\n# \"Everybody Knows\" - 3:45\n# \"Flying Without Wings\" (Video) - 3:40\n\n; CD2\n# \"Flying Without Wings\" - 3:35\n# \"That's What It's All About\" - 3:20\n# \"Flying Without Wings\" <small>(Acappella)</small> - 3:29\n* '''Australia'''\n# \"Flying Without Wings\" - 3:35\n# \"I Have a Dream\" (Remix) - 4:06\n# \"Seasons in the Sun\" (Single Remix) - 4:10\n# \"Flying Without Wings\" (Video) - 3:40\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Charts (1999/2000/2018)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|31|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings|note=Triple A-side with \"[[I Have a Dream (song)#Westlife version|I Have a Dream]]\" and \"[[Seasons in the Sun]]\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|7|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia Tip|8|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Denmark|Danish]] Airplay Chart\n|align=\"center\"|45\n|-\n{{singlechart|Denmark|14|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|19|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings|note=Double A-side with \"I Have a Dream\"}}\n|-\n|Europe ([[Eurochart Hot 100]])<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_fAgEAAAAMBAJ|quote=westlife.|title=Billboard|first=Nielsen Business Media|last=Inc|date=13 November 1999|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n{{singlechart|Finland|17|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|85|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings|songid=56881|accessdate=3 March 2020}}\n|-\n|Ireland ([[Irish Singles Chart|IRMA]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n{{singlechart|Norway|7|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|6|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Scotland|2|date=1999-10-24}}\n|-\n|[[Gaon Digital Chart|South Korea (Gaon Weekly BGM Chart)]]<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/chart/digital.php \n |title=Gaon Weekly BGM Chart \n |work=Gaon Chart \n |publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association \n |accessdate=July 5, 2019 \n |language=Korean \n |df=mdy \n}}\n*{{cite web\n |url=http://mobile.gaonchart.co.kr/searchList.gaon?serviceGbn=S1060&nationGbn=T&yyyy=2019&condition=2&search_str=Flying Without Wings\n |title=Flying Without Wings\n |date=July 5, 2019\n |archivedate=July 5, 2019 \n}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center\" |72\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|12|artist=Westlife|song=Flying Without Wings}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|1|artist=Westlife|artistid=7712}}\n|-\n|UK Radio Airplay Chart\n